<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-08-03T06:49:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-08-03T06:49:00-05:00" n="345" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d345">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 838.00/618.</note>
                        <head>[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-08-03T07:00:00-04:49"><hi rend="smallcaps">August</hi> 3, 1911—7 <hi rend="smallcaps">a.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>The German war vessel landed about 40 men at 10 o’clock, although there
                            was no apparent necessity for such action, as from personal observation
                            the streets were quiet and deserted.</p>
